metadata.name: Glomularus #132
metadata.description:
Glomularus is an exploration in generative, artificial life forms. The project is an extension of my Protobyte series, begun in 2004.

Driven by Verlet icosahedra and responsive tendrils, Glomulari live in a spherical virtual ecosystem (V-eco) enhanced through user interaction.

Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
  drag -> camera rotation
  drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
  scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
  1-9: add acceleration
  -, +: reduce | increase V-eco sphere radius
  f, g: reduce | increase fog
  p: screen capture

Tip:
To decrease creature acceleration, reduce V-eco sphere radius

Note:
Please post your favorite Glomularus screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with Three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #54
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.description:
Возвышение (Eng.: Elevation) is the next step of my study of Suprematism, textures and colours, partially inspired by Lazar Khidekel works. 
The work depicts the superiority of the simplest geometric forms and colours over everything else.

metadata.name: blub blub #79
metadata.description:
blub blub is an exploration of form.

We begin with two simple shapes, one defining the shape that will be drawn, the other defining the path along which it will traverse.

Each shape is then paired with a sinusoid that either modifies the size of the shape that is drawn, or the offset from the path it is traversing.

This simple set of rules leads to a surprising large variety of forms.

metadata.name: Overgrowth #46
metadata.description:
This work is an exploration of random growth focused on three interconnected elements. The first is a randomly moving brush, the second is one is an alternating overlay of white and black circles along bezier points between brush movements, and the final one being a continually decreasing brush size.

The overall result gives a complex scribble art effect. 

Created with p5.js

metadata.name: Smoke #88
metadata.description:
Inspired by the hot weather of the city.
Made in August 2022, Milano, Italy.

5 visible Features:
-Mood: tender, bleed, icecream, summer in Milano, evening, futurepunk, acid, love
-Size: small, regular, big
-Density: low, moderate, high, very high
-Speed: slow, moderate, fast
-Emissions: from 2 to 9

Some of the features are very rare, others less, some more common.

The design is being optimized to render at different speeds depending on the size of the window. The smaller the size, the faster the render and lower the detail, viceversa bigger the size, slower the render and higher the detail.
The moire effect of lines that are making the shades of the artwork will look thick with a low resolution, and become finer and more detailed the higher the resolution. You can use this feature to create quick previews or to save very Hi-Resolution images.
To save an image with the size of the window press S once the image is fully rendered.
The fx(hash) thumbnail is saved at 1425px x 1900px.
To save a Hi-Resolution image 3000px x 4000px press H and wait, the page will reload and start to render. Please be patient.

Built using p5js, published under CC-BY-NC-4.0 license.

Once the collection will be fully minted, the variations button will be disabled.

metadata.name: Impression of Rolling Sphere #180
metadata.description:
"Impression of Rolling Sphere" by UeShiba is a piece that has different interpretations and so many thoughts, ways of seeing it. The artist’s work inspires feelings and emotions from its beauty to the mindfulness of the subject. It is an interesting time as people see life primarily through a different lens.

The gallery explores what it means to have a relation with this painting, how one can perceive it differently, or how they can just appreciate it for what it is: a beautiful piece of art that may give you somatic sensations or even a philosophical thought.

I suggests that this small, sphere is impression of the universe and within ourselves, one can feel the flow of nature, communication between people and with life itself.

metadata.name: Rug of imagination #90
metadata.description:
I recently faced covid, I can say it was one of the worst moments of my life, I questioned my sanity and if I would stay alive. What comforted me was to remember my childhood, my past, and I remembered the rugs I used to sit on to play or listen to stories, it is amazing how in the day to day we forget the little things in life that make us happy, sometimes we stop living to just survive.

Artwork made with p5.js and p5.scribbles
